import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Card from '../../../components/Card.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Projects" description="The process every project follows: Requirements → Design → Architecture → Implement → Test → Deploy → UAT → Monitor.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Projects</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Every project in this course follows the same sequence — the standard software development lifecycle (SDLC). The product gets more complex each time, but the process stays the same. Learn it once, use it forever.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">AI changes the <em>how</em>, not the <em>what</em> or the <em>why</em>. You move from maker to director — but you never lose ownership.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">In early projects, most steps have been done for you — so you can focus on learning the tools and the build loop. In later projects, you'll own every step.</p>

  <!-- The Process -->
  <h2 class="mb-6 mt-10">The Process</h2>

  <div class="space-y-8 mb-12">

    <!-- 1. Requirements -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Requirements & Product Definition</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Define <em>what</em> you're building. It starts with a client conversation — "I need a website for my business" — and turns that into structured requirements: features, acceptance criteria, user stories, and crucially, what you're <em>not</em> building (anti-scope).</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">A good requirements doc is specific enough that someone could verify the finished product against it. Not "the site should look good" but "the hero image is under 200KB and loads in under 3 seconds."</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Define the problem, user stories, acceptance criteria</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Refine ambiguous requirements, generate stories from a brief, spot gaps</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 2. Design -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Design</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">The design defines how the product <em>looks and behaves</em>. In a professional project, this might be wireframes, a Figma file, or a full design system — covering user flows, page layouts, responsive behaviour, interactions, and visual details like colours, typography, and spacing.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Define UX intent and user flows, validate against user needs</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Generate wireframe concepts, suggest UI patterns, prototype layouts</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 3. Architecture -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Architecture</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">The architecture document defines <em>how to build it</em> technically — what technologies to use, how to structure the code, how data flows through the system, and how the pieces connect.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">The architecture also produces the <strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> — the project memory file that Claude Code reads at the start of every session. It's the architecture distilled into instructions for AI: tech stack, repo structure, anti-scope rules, engineering standards.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Understand enough to challenge AI's proposals</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Propose system design, data models, API contracts, tech stack rationale</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 4. Implementation -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">4</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Implementation</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">This is where you direct AI through the tickets, one at a time. The backlog breaks the architecture into ordered tickets — then each one follows the same loop:</p>
      <ol class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-decimal list-inside space-y-1">
        <li>You tell Claude to start the ticket</li>
        <li>Claude creates a branch, implements, commits, opens a PR</li>
        <li>Claude and Gemini both review the code</li>
        <li>You verify against the acceptance criteria — open the product, test it, try to break it</li>
        <li>You decide: merge it, or direct Claude to fix something</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Direct, review, iterate on AI output. Work in prompts, specs, code review</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Write the majority of the code</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 5. Testing -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">5</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Testing</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Verify the product works. For a static site, this means Lighthouse audits, DevTools checks, and testing on a real phone. For a dynamic app, it means automated tests — unit, integration, and end-to-end.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Validate tests cover the acceptance criteria from step 1</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Generate test cases, write unit/integration tests, identify edge cases</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 6. Deployment -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">6</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Deployment</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Ship to a staging URL. You verify it works on a real server — not just on your laptop. Test on a real phone. Check that links work, images load, and performance is acceptable.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Set up once, then automated</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Write pipeline configs, Dockerfiles, IaC</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 7. UAT -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">7</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">UAT (User Acceptance Testing)</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">Show the client the staging URL. They'll have feedback — things you missed, things they changed their mind about, small fixes. This is normal, not failure. You turn their feedback into small tickets, fix them with the same loop, then get sign-off.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Humans validating with humans. The client doesn't care how it was built</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">No change — this is a human step</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Connector -->
    <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="w-[1.5px] h-6 bg-border"></div></div>

    <!-- 8. Monitoring & Iteration -->
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-primary-bg text-primary font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">8</div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Monitoring & Iteration</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-3">The client has signed off. Go live on their domain. Point DNS, verify everything loads, then monitor and iterate. What went well? What did AI get wrong? Lessons feed into the next project.</p>
      <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-border grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">You:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Own the feedback loop, decide what to iterate on</span></div>
        <div class="text-xs"><span class="font-semibold text-text">AI:</span> <span class="text-text-secondary">Interpret logs, suggest fixes, analyse usage patterns</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- Project cards -->
  <h2 class="mb-6 mt-10 pt-8 border-t border-border">Choose a project</h2>
  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <Card title="Project 1: The Static Site" subtitle="GreenScape Landscaping — a business website deployed to a real URL. 8 tickets." href="/web-dev/projects/1" />
    <Card title="Project 2: The Dynamic App" subtitle="FactFeed — database, API, Docker, CI, and automated testing. 11 tickets." href="/web-dev/projects/2" />
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
